<br>
&quot;UNICEF figures show that over 1 in 5 Iraqi children remain malnourished.&quot;<br>
<br>
Deaths are an expected part of war.  An unfortunate reality.  If your going to harp on every death to try and play the sympathy card, then I can see why France gave up so easliy to the Germans. <br>
<br>
Liberation has always come with a price.  WWI and WWII were won with innocent deaths, sacrifices by our troops, and a resolve to win.  In this age of instant war coverage, the media in it's need for constant news gives us what we want.  In WWI, WWII, Vietnam, Korea, etc, it took weeks for news to be gathered and reported.  <br>
<br>
But I am certain innocent deaths took place in the opening days of those wars, yet the war continued.  If fact, every war throughout history has involved countless deaths of innocents, destruction, loss of lives.<br>
<br>
The threat of terrorism against the US has always been there.  It's not going away if the US stops the attack against Iraq.  As Taranna is fond of saying, US policy in the Middle East is the reason for terrorism against the US.  Add the Israeli/Palestinian issue to the mex, I believe invading Iraq is nothing. <br>
<br>
The UN, the great savior, responsible for millions of deaths in the name of doing good.  Even this nobel institution has blood on it's hands.  But perhaps the way they deal in death is more acceptable.<br>
<br>
Former Yugoslavia:<br>
In a rare move, the United Nations has taken itself to task in a report on its performance before and during a massacre which claimed the lives of thousands during the Bosnian war. The report is a frank and harsh account of the U.N.'s response to the killings in 1994 at Srebrenica. <br>
<br>
So far, at least 2,500 bodies have been recovered from Srebrenica and thousands of Muslims are still missing. They are believed to have been killed after Serb forces overran what was said by the U.N. to be a safe haven. <br>
 <br>
Rwanda:<br>
Some 800,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were slaughtered by Hutu extremists between April and June 1994. The UN had 2,000 peacekeepers in Rwanda before the genocide but it started to withdraw them as the killing began. When the scale of the slaughter became clear, the UN authorised more troops to be sent to Rwanda, but they did not arrive in time to prevent the massacres. <br>
<br>
East Timor:<br>
In late August 1999, the UN and now Secretary General Annan, called for elections on the small island country of East Timor despite disturbing evidence that hard line elements in the Indonesian military were preparing to cause wide spread public disorder so as to disrupt the elections. The UN failed to provide adequate protection for the civilian population. Dili was burnt to the ground and East Timor was engulfed in violence. After weeks of killing and millions of dollars of damage, the Australian government sent in ground troops to restore order to East Timor; but by then, it was too late to save East Timor from UN bungling.<br>
<br>
Support in Iraq:<br>
You say the civilian population in Iraq hate the US and dont' want to be liberated.  Well I disagree.  The Kurds to the North are more than willing to fight, as resistance in the South is slowing gaining ground.  The population is more cautious in it's support due to the betrayal they felt in the first Gulf War. So regaining that support will be a slow process.  (poor kurds, they probably gonna get shafted again)  Did you read about the Iraqi troops firing on it's own population with mortars to keep them from leaving Basra for aid?  And the Human Shields?  Real love for Iraqis there.<br>
<br>
Basiclly your stating broad feelings on how bad war is and trying to play the sympathy card with one sided stories in your last post.  Nothing new gleamed, nothing new learned, same one sided presentation.<br>
<br>
PNAC quote:<br>
This is not a yes or no type of question.  America is a democratic based country where we elect representatives who we feel will act in our best interest.  These representatives will then make decisions based on their own beliefs, opinions of fellow law makers, interest of supporters back home, or to lobbyists.  The leaders, aka President, leaders of congress, leaders of the senate, will then make policy and enforce it.  <br>
<br>
Yes I agree that leaders can bring the population around to their way of thinking, because it's the people who elect the multiple officials who put them into office.  If a policy is wrong, then the people will voice their disapproval at the polls for new leaders.  The new leaders then make new policy, and the process repeats itself.  Time is the determining factor for which policy shall be judged as success or not.<br>
<br>
<br>
