Edit2: Link to above at the Heritage Foundation -- <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.heritage.org/Research/MiddleEast/wm217.cfm#_ftnref25">www.heritage.org/Research...#_ftnref25</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->  and link to the Stockhom International Peace Research Institute (SIPRI) page -- <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.sipri.se/">www.sipri.se/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kadandrumtally>Kadandrum Tally</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cartooncars.com/images/print/bmw/e46m3silv.jpg" BORDER=0> at: 3/31/03 12:46:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 657<br> <font color=#333333>(3/31/03 2:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1939.topic&index=165>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: god bless our troops and allies</span><hr size=1> Firstly to address Kadandrum's points:<br>
The essence of the first part of your post was that French companies currently do 1.5 billion of business with Iraq under oil for food, and that up to rougly $5 billion dollars of business in total is planned.  For a start the oil for food programme numbers are nonsense because oil for food is ongoing and will continue to be so regardless of the war.  As for the rest...  I'm not sure how much you know about economic figures Kad, but that's quite frankly peanuts.  It's less than a tenth of the US's budget for this war, less than a fifth of the UK's budget for the war.  <br>
<br>
Out of France's GDP of 1.2 <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>trillion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> dollars, potentially 3.5 billion, a little more than 1/1000th of the French economy might be lost because of the war.  OH NOES!  I mean, France's economic growth of 0.3% in 2001 was disastrous, but even assuming a repeat of that, 3/1000ths of economic growth easily absorbs the loss of 1/1000, they'll barely notice.  Saying France opposed the war for economic reasons is utterly thick, they could reinvest the money at the drop of a hat in any number of other oil ventures.  Not least of which is British North Sea oil, which as trade within the EU is tax-free and less cost to transport.<br>
<br>
The same is true of the Germans, an economy of 1.85 trillion isn't even going to flinch if a few million in trade goes astray, it'll just find other markets in Europe.  Lower transport costs, 0 tax on goods crossing EU borders and funding incentives from the EU for trading with a European partner.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>c. Soviet-era debt of $7 billion through $8 billion was generated by arms sales to Iraq during the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
HAHAHA, you're joking right?  The US and UK sold a combined worth of 250 billion dollars of arms to Saddam prior to and during the first two years of the Iran-Iraq war.  We completely crowded those pesky Ruskies out of the market and rightly so!  After all, our weapons are that much more lethal, particularly chemical agents as those Kurds found out in Hallabja.  Reagan was still smiling though, so it was all good I suppose.  Even more hilarious was the sight of Donald Rumsfeld, the man who sold Saddam billions of dollars worth of weaponry, and gave him millions more in credit to buy weapons...telling Syria to stop selling Iraq weapons!  What's good for the goose is certainly good for the gander I suppose eh?  After all, if the US has peddled weapons to Iraq, why shouldn't the Syrians?<br>
<br>
Russia certainly does have more to lose than France, but that's not saying much.  Their GDP is 320 billion, but their economy grew by 29% last year, so a minor loss of trade will hardly hurt such a bullish economy.  Most nations suffered horribly in 2001 trade-wise, Russia was one of the brightest spots around the globe in that regard.<br>
<br>
As for China...lol.  Without including Hong Kong, their GDP is 1.1 trillion US dollars, their trade with Iraq is a microscopic dot on a microscopic dot compared to their open trade with North Korea and Pakistan.  Those 25 F-16s the US sold to the military dictarship currently ruling Pakistan are worth more than the sum of China's trade with Iraq since 1990.  Citing economic reasons for these nations being involved is irrelevant, these nations would barely be affected.  A link listing GDPs:  <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.e-edge.org/special/GDP.htm">www.e-edge.org/special/GDP.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Saying these nations oppose a war because of oil/trade is as laughable as saying the US is supporting this war for oil/trade.  That may seem to be a theme of the protesters marching in the US Kad, but you don't see it here in Europe.  Most people here oppose the war because they think we'll all suffer as a result- people aren't stupid enough to think that even Rumsfeld would send American troops to die for a few oil companies.  Nor should people in the US be stupid enough to think France opposed this war because they risked losing a thousandth of their economy.  Opposing the US is a huge political risk at the best of times- on a point of war it'd take a hell of a lot more than that meagre trade relationship to sway the diplomacy of a nation like France.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, on to lurkers arguments, if they can be called that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What's in this war against Iraq? You are stating obvious things that don't really further your argument. The Iraqi people may die as collateral damage in this war, or die under Saddam's brutal regime<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not at all a statement of the obvious- my point was that where sanctions backed mainly by the US have pushed Iraq into a humanitarian crisis, this war has turned it into a disaster area.  60% of Iraqis depend on the oil for food programme to survive, and as a result of the war the aid isn't getting through.  The RFAV <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sir Galahad</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is carrying 200 tonnes of aid to the people of Southern Iraq, it's true.  But guess what, you would need 80 such shipments <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a day</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to even break even with the oil for food programme.  Never mind the people who were suffering in spite of that.<br>
<br>
In Basra we've seen water and power facilities attacked and deliberately disrupted, in that city of 2 million people, nearly 400,000 children have been deemed to be at risk of death due to thirst or malnourishment.  Speaking of which:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;UNICEF figures show that over 1 in 5 Iraqi children remain malnourished.&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If you think that constitutes your case for going to war you're far more naive than I thought.  Here's a little eye-opener:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.unicefusa.org/ssc/global.html">www.unicefusa.org/ssc/global.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
That's right lurker!  The global malnourishment level for children is almost 1 in 3.  So in fact, as brutal as the Iraqi regime is, they're doing a better job at feeding their children than North Korea, China, or Pakistan.  China has a huge population problem- but North Korea?  2/3 children in North Korea go hungry to bed at night lurker.  Pakistan is a dictatorship, a brutal regime, with far worse humanitarian difficulties as a result of a military government that cares nothing for its people.  Are you advocating the US invade them too lurker?  Those damn nick-nacks obviously can't govern themselves so you'll bomb the shite out of them and show them how right?  Wrong.  <br>
<br>
Both nations are nuclear-capable, so despite the fact they are far more brutal regimes than Saddam's you're happy to do nothing there I take it.  All your talk of bravery, death and sacrifice for liberty sounds hollow if you consider the US position towards these far more destructive regimes.  The policy as usual seems to be- &quot;support the dictators we like or are too afraid of, bomb the shite out of the ones we don't like/daren't touch&quot;  Except that none of those bombs have touched Saddam- like the sanctions your government trumpeted, it is the Iraqi people who are being made victims of this &quot;solution&quot;.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Liberation has always come with a price. WWI and WWII were won with innocent deaths, sacrifices by our troops, and a resolve to win.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If you truly believe the situations can be compared, you either haven't been reading my posts/the news, or you're truly thick.  Those wars were a matter of national survival you imbecile, nations were fighting across borders against an expansionist power which had overwhelming military force.  Saddam is neither expansionist (Kuwait was always historically the 19th province of Iraq) nor is in possession of overwhelming mlitary force.  And Iraq does not threaten our national survival- so where is the need for this war again?  Nowhere in your post have you given a good reason for it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The threat of terrorism against the US has always been there. It's not going away if the US stops the attack against Iraq.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Did I ever say it would?  I said it would get worse, and every security expert consulted agrees with me.  Who's misdirecting now lurker?<br>
<br>
Regarding Rwanda, Bosnia and Kosovo- those were situations where internal genocide occured within a nation.  Where's the genocide in Iraq lurker?  And if you're going to pull out the long and bloody record of the Iraqi regime....firstly that's not genocide.  In fact it's a good deal less bloody than Pakistan, Saudi Arabia or Israel- more Palestinians have died at Israeli hands since 1967 than innocent Iraqis have under Saddam Hussein.  All those nations I mention are your allies lurker- why aren't you invading them?  Heck, why are you allies? :P  Another thing you conveniently ignore is that while the UN was involved late in those scenarios because of its unwillingness to involve itself in civil wars within a nation-state, it did ultimately get involved.  <br>
<br>
Not because the US lead the way, but because France did.  Yes, the now hated French were the co-submitters of the resolutions authorising military force in Bosnia and in Rwanda- the US wasn't.  In fact, the US was opposed to involvement in Rwanda, whether by itself or the UN- a similar veto threat killed two resolutions pre-dating UN involvement in Rwanda.  And it is UN mandates that are now successfully putting these nations back together lurker, not a retired US general administering a protectorate.<br>
<br>
Regarding East Timor- you have absolutly no idea what you're talking about.  ASEAN sent a regional coalition of forces to act as peace-keepers long before Australian troops were committed to the area.  What's more, it was a UN mandate that allowed for the legal rights of Timor Timur as a self-determined area, on the road to nationhood.  Foreign troops may have helped (under a UN mandate) to resolve a civil conflict, but they were asked in, they didn't invade.  And they didn't hang about either, most of them withdrew after the conflict, which lasted all of 2 weeks.  The more you look at East Timor, the more you'd realize that it was pretty well an unqualified success from the moment the UN was involved.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The population is more cautious in it's support due to the betrayal they felt in the first Gulf War. So regaining that support will be a slow process<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If that was true, then why are 40-50,000 Iraqi exiles in Jordan getting on buses and heading back into Iraq to fight?  Swapping a relatively cushy life in Jordan for a war-torn nation uncertain of its future is an act of patriotism, not uncertainty.  While I agree that a good many in the south of Iraq are mistrustful- central and northern Iraqi tribes, particularly the Tikriti and Basvani tribes will support Saddam to the end.  These aren't fanatical Fedayeen or regular forces- just ordinary citizens prepared to resist any foreign occupation.  They look at the plight of the Palestinians and think to themselves &quot;I don't want to live like that, I don't want my life to be lived at the sufferance of a foreign power&quot;.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Basiclly your stating broad feelings on how bad war is <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You really don't understand my argument at all.  My point is not that war is bad, but that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>this</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> war is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>unecessary</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and always was.  Not only that, but I argued that if war had to come, it should have international backing.  This isn't a nation acting in self-defence, nor acting to help another nation defending itself.  This is aggression, plain and simple- and for wars that deal with the internal affairs of a sovreign state you need overwhelming international support for the peace to be won afterwards.  <br>
<br>
With a UN mandate and an Arab coalition, the Iraqi regime were forced to back down and surrender in 1991- the region was against them, the will of the international community was against them.  The Saddam regime will fight to the bitter end as long as they are convinced the Arab world and their people support them.  That is why international support was crucial, why any war would have been far less bloody with the peace more certain if consensus was honestly sought.  It wasn't, and the consequences are as I've stated.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes I agree that leaders can bring the population around to their way of thinking, because it's the people who elect the multiple officials who put them into office.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How very interesting.  What I didn't tell you lurker, was that although that quote did indeed come from Donald Rumsfeld speaking to the PNAC, he was quoting someone else:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://pic5.picturetrail.com/VOL81/616617/969437/21919042.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
That's right- Rumsfeld was quoting Reichsmarshall Herman Goering, the commander of the Nazi Luftwaffe.  There's a chilling amount of truth in those words, especially in the way the Bush administration has sold this war.  The Nazis were not a democratic government, yet they had huge, massive overwhelming popular support.  Such was their support that nearly half a dozen countries under the Nazi glove had thousands willing to fight for the Reich, even the SS- two SS brigades were Czech for example.  They didn't call it a coalition of the willing at the time, but there certainly is resonance with the &quot;you're either with us or against us&quot; part of the Bush &amp; Nazi doctrines.  Support them, and you get a kind word and a say in the way conquered territories are administered and profited from.  Speak against them- and you face either terrible military force, or isolation (Sweden &amp; Switzerland had their borders closed to trade)<br>
<br>
I'm not making a direct comparison of governments, just of particular points of policy- it's no less chilling, even with that qualification I make.  How easily people are persuaded to support, even fight for wrongful, sometimes evil policies doesn't seem to have changed much in the US lurker.  One of the main reasons Germany and France are so vehemently against this war is that they well remember how easily so many people were willing to die for or passively support a wrongful cause.  They don't want to be caught on the wrong side again, they want international institutes to work.  And it'll take more than Freedom Fries and people not buying wine to sway that position of principle.  Bush is burning his bridges with these countries and using what's left to fan the flames of terror that will surely threaten us ever increasingly as this war goes on.  You have argued that terrorists can be deterred by this war lurker.  I'll end my post with this question:  How do you propose to deter a hateful fanatic who cares nothing for his own life, if even the Israelis can't?  That question would trouble any intelligent leader's sleep.  Guess Dubyah's ok though!<br>
