Note though, in the report the soldiers said that no special forces soldier &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>ever witnessed any atrocities committed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;.  Doran's film, in interviewing the people associated with the massacre shows that US Special forces handed over most of these prisoners over to Northern Alliance control knowing full well what would happen to them.  Did the SS generals sitting behind desks have to witness the concentration camp Stalags in order to be guilty of war-crimes?  Of course not.  Handing someone over to be executed is to be complicit in the act of execution, that is a fundamental principle in law.<br>
<br>
The way that the Captain worded his statement carefully reminds me of Reichensturmfuhrer Hermann Reugen when he said at the Nuremberg trials:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> &quot;I never saw any such camps, nor did I hear my colleagues in the Schultzstaffel speak of them except in passing.  I assumed they were normal prison camps.  You ask me if I could have prevented some of the deaths if I tried to find out about what happened at the camps.  Well perhaps I could if I had aggressively pursued it.  But the fate of undesirables was a political decision not a military one.  Making a nuisance in this way was no way for a soldier to behave, particularly not a soldier who wants to remain in his government's good graces&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It's clear to me that the fate of Taliban soldiers captured was pre-determined by political figures in the Bush administration, Camp X-Ray and the beating to death of two prisoners at Bagram air-base (linked in the PoW thread) demonstrates that clearly enough.  Individual soldiers distancing themselves from what happened isn't good enough- it's understandable, but unacceptable.  Looking the other way was never a defence against war-crimes- but this and other incidents in Afghanistan certainly must have contributed to the firmness of the Bush administration's stance about refusing to ratify the international criminal court (ICC).<br>
<br>
