<br>
I don't take &quot;2 hours&quot; to write my posts, most of them take no more than 5 minutes, the links are all mainstream British newspapers and are easy to find.  There might well be links and opinions that challenge my opinions- but one thing that is being overlooked is this.  At one extreme of the spectrum you have Fox News, Rush Limbaugh et al.  At the other extreme end of the spectrum you have Al-Jazeera, Al-Fahds, the Socialist Worker, Der Spiegel, Le Figaro, etc.  <br>
<br>
British opinion and mainstream public opinion in Europe lies right in the middle of those two extremes, and that was the reasoning behind my choice of mainstream UK papers- since extremist views help no one.  I might well be &quot;selling myself short&quot; by posting here- but I don't agree that this isn't the best place for a discussion.  People discuss such issues on the train, in a pub, anywhere really.  And why not?  These are issues that affect us all- there is no &quot;inappropriate place&quot; in my opinion.  If you think differently, that's your right- and no one's forcing you to read anything, or listen to two people discussing it in a pub or cafe.  If I overheard two people discussing boy bands in a library, I may think it's the &quot;inappropriate&quot; place, but I wouldn't go up to them and tell them to their face it was inappropriate.  After all, why should they censor their behaviour because of what I think?<br>
<br>
 Yes, living your life in a free and open society is the greatest gift.  Democracy however, is an act of empowerment, you can't export it like cigarettes, nor impose it with armoured battalions.  I have Iraqi friends and colleagues at work Justi- they may have fled an oppressive regime, but they have no love for foreign armies occupying their soil.  They look at other Arab dictatorships in the region with US troops on their soil, they look at the plight of the Palestinians...and that is the source of their mistrust.  Having terrified relatives on the phone from Baghdad to Basra doesn't help, nor are reports that their nephews and nieces haven't eaten in 10 days of conflict.  <br>
<br>
One of my clinical staff has resigned from his post to go back to Iraq in order to attend the funeral of his sister, shot at a checkpoint yesterday.  He may have fled his country because of the regime there, but I can't imagine he'll be feeling any joy at being &quot;liberated&quot;.  Call these sob stories if you will, diminish them in the bigger picture if you will.  I won't- even if Salem wasn't someone I'd worked with for 5 years, shared a pint and a laugh with, I'd still have the human decency not to turn his loss into a statistic. <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
